   "source": [
    "# Fitting temperature data\n",
    "\n",
    "Here are the 5-year temperature averages again."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "year = 1955:5:2000\n",
    "t = year .- 1955;\n",
    "y = [ -0.0480, -0.0180, -0.0360, -0.0120, -0.0040,\n",
    "    0.1180, 0.2100, 0.3320, 0.3340, 0.4560 ];"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The standard best-fit line results from using a linear polynomial that meets the least squares criterion."

   "source": [
    "using Polynomials,Plots\n",
    "p = Polynomial(c)\n",
    "f = s -> p(s-1955)\n",
    "\n",
    "scatter(year,y,label=\"data\",\n",
    "    xlabel=\"year\",ylabel=\"anomaly (degrees C)\",leg=:bottomright)\n",
    "plot!(f,1955,2000,label=\"linear fit\")"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If we use a global cubic polynomial, the points are fit more closely."
